## LU factorisation

Gaussian elimination  can be interpreted as an LU factorisation. Write a matrix
$A âˆˆ ğ”½^{n Ã— n}$ as follows:
$$
A =  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\ ğ¯_1 & K_1 \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $Î±_1 = a_{11}$, $ğ¯_1 = A[2:n, 1]$ and $ğ°_1 = A[1, 2:n]$ (that is, $ğ¯_1 âˆˆ ğ”½^{n-1}$ is a vector whose entries are the 2nd through last row of the first column of $A$ whilst $ğ°_1 âˆˆ ğ”½^{n-1}$ is a vector containing the 2nd through last entries in the last column of $A$). Gaussian elimination consists of taking the first row, dividing by
$Î±_1$ and subtracting from all other rows. That is equivalent to multiplying by a lower triangular matrix:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & I \end{bmatrix} A = \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & K_1 -ğ¯_1ğ°_1^âŠ¤ /Î±_1 \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $A_2 := K_1 -ğ¯_1ğ°_1^âŠ¤ /Î±_1$  happens to be a rank-1 perturbation of $K_1$.
We can write this another way:
$$
A = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
$$
Now assume we continue this process and manage to deduce an LU factorisation $A_2 = L_2 U_2$.
Then
$$
A = L_1 \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & L_2U_2 \end{bmatrix}
= \underbrace{L_1 \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
 & L_2 \end{bmatrix}}_L  \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & U_2 \end{bmatrix}}_U
$$
Note we can multiply through to find
$$
L = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & L_2 \end{bmatrix}.
$$
Noting that if $A âˆˆ ğ”½^{1 Ã— 1}$ then it has a trivial LU factorisation we can use the above construction to proceed recursively until we arrive at the trivial case.


**Example (LU by-hand)**
Consider the matrix
$$
