## PLU factorisation

We learned in first year linear algebra that if a diagonal entry is zero
when doing Gaussian elimination one has to _row pivot_. For stability,
in implementation one may wish to pivot even if the diagonal entry is nonzero: swap the largest in magnitude entry for the entry on the diagonal turns out to be significantly more stable than standard LU.

This is equivalent to a PLU decomposition. Here we use a _permutation matrix_, whose action on a vector permutes its entries, as discussed in the appendix. That is, consider a
permutation which we identify with a vector ${\mathbf Ïƒ} = [Ïƒ_1,â€¦,Ïƒ_n]$ containing the integers $1,â€¦,n$ exactly once. The permutation operator represents the action of permuting the entries in a vector:
$$
P_Ïƒ(ğ¯) := ğ¯[{\mathbf Ïƒ}] = \Vectt[v_{Ïƒ_1},â‹®,v_{Ïƒ_n}]
$$
This is a linear operator, and hence we can identify it with a _permutation matrix_ $P_Ïƒ âˆˆ â„^{n Ã— n}$ (more precisely the entries  of $P_Ïƒ$ are either 1 or 0). Importantly, products of permutation matrices are also permutation matrices and permutation matrices are orthogonal, that is, $P_Ïƒ^{-1} = P_Ïƒ^\top$.


**Theorem (PLU)** A matrix $A âˆˆ â„‚^{n Ã— n}$ is invertible if and only if it has a PLU decomposition:
$$
A = P^âŠ¤ L U
$$
where the diagonal of $L$ are all equal to 1 and the diagonal of $U$ are all non-zero, and $P$ is a permutation matrix.

**Proof**

If we have a PLU decomposition of this form then $L$ and $U$ are invertible and hence the inverse is simply $A^{-1} = U^{-1} L^{-1} P$. Hence we consider the orther direction.


If $A âˆˆ â„‚^{1 Ã— 1}$ we trivially have an LU decomposition $A = [1] * [a_{11}]$ as all $1 Ã— 1$ matrices are triangular.
We now proceed by induction: assume all invertible matrices of lower dimension have a PLU factorisation.
As $A$ is invertible not all entries in the first column are zero. Therefore there exists a permutation
$P_1$ so that $Î± := (P_1 A)[1,1] â‰ Â 0$. Hence we write
$$
P_1 A = \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\
                        ğ¯ & K
                        \end{bmatrix} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯/Î± & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & K - ğ¯ ğ°^âŠ¤/Î± \end{bmatrix}
$$
We deduce that $A_2 := K - ğ¯ ğ°^âŠ¤/Î±$ is invertible because $A$ and $L_1$ are invertible
(Exercise).

By assumption we can write $A_2 = P_2^âŠ¤ L_2 U_2$. Thus we have:
$$
\begin{align*}
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\
            & P_2 \end{bmatrix} P_1}_P A &= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\
            & P_2 \end{bmatrix}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\
                        ğ¯ & A_2
                        \end{bmatrix}  =
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ & P_2 \end{bmatrix} L_1  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & P_2^âŠ¤ L_2  U_2 \end{bmatrix} \\
            &= \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
P_2 ğ¯/Î± & P_2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &  \\  &  P_2^âŠ¤ L_2  \end{bmatrix}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  &  U_2 \end{bmatrix} \\
&= \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
P_2 ğ¯/Î± & L_2  \end{bmatrix}}_L \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  &  U_2 \end{bmatrix}}_U. \\
\end{align*}
$$

